# Frontend Scroll/Overflow Scope Rule

Do not add global scroll/overflow overrides in feature CSS or template inline styles.

## Never use global selectors for feature fixes

- Forbidden in feature files: `body`, `html`, `.main-content`, `.content-section`, `.app-container` with `overflow`, `height`, or `position` overrides.
- Forbidden pattern: broad selectors with `!important` that are not scoped to a single section.

## Required scoping

- Scope all feature layout fixes to the feature root id (example: `#appsSection ...`, `#settingsImportMediaSection ...`).
- If a fix is only for one page, selectors must start with that page/section root.
- Prefer removing legacy hacks over adding new `!important` overrides.

## Safe pattern

```css
/* GOOD: section-scoped */
#appsSection .app-content-panel { overflow: hidden; }
```

```css
/* BAD: leaks to whole app */
.content-section, .app-content-panel { overflow: hidden !important; }
```

## Verification before finishing

Run:

`rg -n "(body|html|\\.main-content|\\.content-section|\\.app-container).*(overflow|height|position)|overflow:\\s*hidden\\s*!important" frontend/static/css frontend/templates/components`

If matches are not section-scoped, fix or remove them.
